erts connected with Hubbers like Kyle Daigle , Martin Woodward , and Avni K=
hatri , and sat in on private panels about AI and open-source careers. If y=
ou=E2=80=99re building community on campus, this is your crew.

=F0=9F=93=8A Octoverse 2025: trends to shape your next project
---------------------------------------------------

( https://octoverse.github.com/ )

Octoverse is GitHub=E2=80=99s annual look at how the world codes=E2=80=94wh=
at languages are growing, how AI is used in real workflows, and where new c=
ontributors are getting started. Use it to decide what to learn next and ho=
w to talk about your work on resumes and in interviews.

* *Language momentum:* TypeScript leads the pack while Python and JavaScrip=
t remain core skills across student projects, internships, and open source.
* *AI in the dev loop:* AI-assisted tasks (tests, refactors, docs, code exp=
loration) continue to grow=E2=80=94use Copilot to accelerate the =E2=80=9Cs=
mall wins=E2=80=9D that unblock bigger features.
* *Onboarding to open source:* First contributions often start with documen=
tation updates, good first issues, and tooling fixes=E2=80=94great entry pa=
ths for class or club projects.
* *Project hygiene matters:* Teams that automate checks (linting, CI, depen=
dency updates) ship more confidently; bring these habits to your next assig=
nment or hackathon.

*Pro tip:* Pull 1=E2=80=932 charts that match your stack and turn them into=
 a bullet on your resume (e.g., =E2=80=9CBuilt a TypeScript + CI pipeline a=
ligned with 2025 Octoverse trends=E2=80=9D).

