    <div class=3D"article-content">
      <p><em>Octoverse</em> is GitHub=E2=80=99s annual look at how the worl=
d codes=E2=80=94what languages are growing, how AI is used in real workflow=
s, and where new contributors are getting started. Use it to decide what to=
 learn next and how to talk about your work on resumes and in interviews.</=
p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Language momentum:</strong> TypeScript leads the pack w=
hile Python and JavaScript remain core skills across student projects, inte=
rnships, and open source.</li>
        <li><strong>AI in the dev loop:</strong> AI-assisted tasks (tests, =
refactors, docs, code exploration) continue to grow=E2=80=94use Copilot to =
accelerate the =E2=80=9Csmall wins=E2=80=9D that unblock bigger features.</=
li>
        <li><strong>Onboarding to open source:</strong> First contributions=
 often start with documentation updates, good first issues, and tooling fix=
es=E2=80=94great entry paths for class or club projects.</li>
        <li><strong>Project hygiene matters:</strong> Teams that automate c=
hecks (linting, CI, dependency updates) ship more confidently; bring these =
habits to your next assignment or hackathon.</li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong>Pro tip:</strong> Pull 1=E2=80=932 charts that match your =
stack and turn them into a bullet on your resume (e.g., =E2=80=9CBuilt a Ty=
peScript + CI pipeline aligned with 2025 Octoverse trends=E2=80=9D).</p>
